  <!--   Chapter  1   -->
  <!--   **********   -->
  <chapter number="1" style="c" sid="JAS 1" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="JAS 1:1" />James, a servant/slave of God and of <char style="it">the</char> Lord Jesus Christ:
    </para>
    <para style="p" vid="JAS 1:1">To <char style="it">the</char> <char style="it">blood-descendants of </char>the<char style="it"> </char>twelve
        tribes <char style="it">of Israel</char><char style="sup">[A]</char> who are among the Diaspora (<char
        style="it">i.e. the scattering of Jews all over the world</char>):
    </para>
    <para style="p" vid="JAS 1:1">I’m delighted to write to you<char style="sup">[a]</char>:<verse eid="JAS 1:1"/>
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="JAS 1:2" />Consider it a joy, my <char style="it">dear </char>comrades, when you <char style="it">by chance </char>fall
        into various tests and trials which find out what you’re made of, <verse eid="JAS 1:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="JAS 1:3" />knowing that the process of proving your faith produces perseverance. <verse eid="JAS 1:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="JAS 1:4" />Let perseverance have <char style="it">the opportunity to become </char>a mature, completed work, in
        order that you would become mature and that every part of you would become complete with nothing left
        out.<verse eid="JAS 1:4" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="JAS 1:5" />But<char style="it"> speaking of things which are left out…</char>If someone is lacking in<char style="sup">[b]</char>
        wisdom, advise him to<char style="sup">[B]</char> simply ask <char style="it">for wisdom </char>from
        the giving-God <char style="it">who’ll grant the request</char> without chewing the person out or demeaning
        him, and it will be given to him. <verse eid="JAS 1:5" />
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="JAS 1:6" />But admonish him to<char style="sup">[B]</char> ask in faith, nothing about him wavering in doubt: you
        see, a person who doubts is like the way that ocean waves are moved and tossed about by the wind. <verse eid="JAS 1:6" />
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="JAS 1:7" />To this point, you should adjust<char style="sup">[B]</char> that person’s expectations so that he does
        not expect to receive anything from the Lord, <verse eid="JAS 1:7" />
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="JAS 1:8" /><char style="it">since he is a</char> double-minded man, irresolute in all his ways.<verse eid="JAS 1:8" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="JAS 1:9" />Get<char style="sup">[B]</char> the Humiliated, Abased Person to glory and take pride in his exaltation,<verse eid="JAS 1:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="JAS 1:10" />and <char style="it">likewise get</char> the rich man <char style="it">to practice</char> humility and
        self-abasement<char style="sup">[C]</char>, because, like the wild flowers of the field<char style="sup">[D]</char>
        which reach an apex when they blossom and then fade back into obscurity, he too will <char style="it">have
        his moment in the sun then </char>pass away <char style="it">and fade back into obscurity</char>. <verse eid="JAS 1:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="JAS 1:11" />You see, the sun rose and dried out the wild flower with its sweltering heat<char style="sup">[c]</char>,
        its flower-part fell off, and the lovely appearance it projected was destroyed—this is the same way that
        the rich man will waste away in his journey <char style="it">through life</char>.<verse eid="JAS 1:11" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="JAS 1:12" />Blessed is <char style="it">the</char> man who perseveres <char style="it">over the course of </char>tests
        and trials, since, after he’s attained approval <char style="it">because of his perseverance,</char>
        he’ll receive the trophy<char style="sup">[d]</char> <char style="it">of a deeply satisfying </char>life<char
        style="sup">[E]</char>, which is promised to those who love Him. <verse eid="JAS 1:12" />
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="JAS 1:13" />Teach<char style="sup">[B]</char> the person who’s being tested by some sort of trial or temptation not
        to say, “I’m being tested by God <char style="it">to see if there’s any evil in me</char>.” You see,
        God is un-tempt-able by any evil; He tempts no one. <verse eid="JAS 1:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="JAS 1:14" />Each person is tempted when he’s lured and dragged off by the passions which are peculiar to him <char
        style="it">and not necessarily to the next person</char>. <verse eid="JAS 1:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="JAS 1:15" />Then once passion or desire has conceived<char style="sup">[F]</char>, it gives birth to sin. When it’s
        finished running its course, sin produces death (<char style="it">i.e., stagnation of waste, joylessness,
        futility, and destruction</char>).<verse eid="JAS 1:15" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="JAS 1:16" />Don’t get led down the primrose path, my dear comrades. <verse eid="JAS 1:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="JAS 1:17" />Every good gift and every perfect present is from <char style="it">the sky</char> above, coming down
        from the Creator of Astronomical Objects (i.e. the sun, the moon, stars, etc.), with whom there is no
        deviation <char style="it">in the movement of such objects</char> and no hint or suggestion of change
        <char style="it">to them</char><char style="sup">[G]</char>. <verse eid="JAS 1:17" />
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="JAS 1:18" />Having planned and decided <char style="it">to do so</char>, he birthed us in<char style="sup">[e]</char>
        a conceptualization<char style="sup">[f]</char> of truth with the end-goal of us being the crème de la
        crème<char style="sup">[g]</char> of His creation.<verse eid="JAS 1:18" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="19" style="v" sid="JAS 1:19" />Be sure you get this down pat, my dear comrades: Each person should see to it<char style="sup">[B]</char>
        that he’s quick to listen, slow to speak, slow to anger<char style="sup">[h]</char>. <verse eid="JAS 1:19" />
      <verse number="20" style="v" sid="JAS 1:20" />You see, a man’s anger won’t live up to God’s standards of right and wrong. <verse eid="JAS 1:20" />
      <verse number="21" style="v" sid="JAS 1:21" />In light of this, once you’ve rid yourself of any filthy residue<char style="sup">[i]</char> of malice,
        with a soft-spoken, gentle self-restraint take to heart and fully embrace the implanted word <char style="it">of
        God</char> which is able to relieve, rescue, and preserve your mind and emotions<char style="sup">[j]</char>.<verse eid="JAS 1:21" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="22" style="v" sid="JAS 1:22" />But become practitioners of a given subject matter<char style="sup">[k]</char> and not just students
        who hear it taught, deceiving themselves <char style="it">because they listen but won’t do, </char><verse eid="JAS 1:22" />
      <verse number="23" style="v" sid="JAS 1:23" />because if somebody hears a subject lectured to him but doesn’t put it into practice, that guy’s like
        a man <char style="it">who looks</char> at himself<char style="sup">[l]</char> in a mirror and gets an
        idea of what he looks like— <verse eid="JAS 1:23" />
      <verse number="24" style="v" sid="JAS 1:24" />you see, he got an idea of what he looks likes, walked away, and immediately forgot what he looks like<char
        style="sup">[H]</char>. <verse eid="JAS 1:24" />
      <verse number="25" style="v" sid="JAS 1:25" />But the fellow who crouched down and looked carefully at a perfect code, a freedom code, and stays put
        <char style="it">looking at it </char>and didn’t become a forgetting-student but became a doing-practitioner,
        that fellow will be blessed in his doing.<verse eid="JAS 1:25" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="26" style="v" sid="JAS 1:26" />If anyone thinks that he <char style="it">strictly adheres to</char> <char style="it">the do’s and don’ts
        of</char> his religion<char style="sup">[I]</char> <char style="it">and</char> isn’t reigning in<char
        style="sup">[m]</char> his tongue but instead kids himself <char style="it">into believing he follows
        his religion strictly</char>—this sort of religion is worthless. <verse eid="JAS 1:26" />
      <verse number="27" style="v" sid="JAS 1:27" />A pure set of religious do’s and don’ts—a set that’s untainted from the Father-God’s<char style="sup">[n]</char>
        point of view—is to visit orphans and widows in dire need for the purpose of helping them, while keeping
        oneself unstained from the world, <char style="it">i.e. the established order of humanity which wants
        nothing to do with God</char>.<verse eid="JAS 1:27" />
    </para>
