    <note caller="[a]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[a]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">I’m delighted to write to you</char>…Lit: <char style="it">joy</char>. A common salutation
        found in the NT; same one in Matt. 26:49; ref. note there.</char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[b]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[b]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">lacking in</char>…Lit: <char style="it">left out</char>. Same verb used in v. 4 <char
        style="it">nothing left out</char>, and this verb is used in the same voice<char style="it">. </char>James
        is obviously using this as a transition.</char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[c]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[c]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">sweltering heat</char>…Lit: <char style="it">burning wind</char></char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[d]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[d]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">trophy</char>…Lit: <char style="it">crown</char> [in this context, a <char style="it">victor’s
        wreath</char>]. Some liberties taken.</char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[e]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[e]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">in</char>…Or: <char style="it">by means of</char></char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[f]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[f]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">conceptualization</char>…Lit: <char style="it">word</char>. Ref. John 1:1.</char>
    </note>
    <note caller="[g]" style="f">
      <char style="fk">[g]</char>
      <char style="ft"><char style="it">crème de la crème</char>…Lit: <char style="it">first-fruits</char>. Ref. note of Rom.
