  <chapter number="3" style="c" sid="JAS 3" />
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="1" style="v" sid="JAS 3:1" />There should not be a lot of you becoming instructors<char style="sup">[A]</char>, my comrades, knowing
        that we’ll be held to a higher standard<char style="sup">[a]</char>. <verse eid="JAS 3:1" />
      <verse number="2" style="v" sid="JAS 3:2" />You see, we all mess up or fall short<char style="sup">[b]</char> in many ways. If a given person doesn’t
        mess up in speech, that fellow has got his act together<char style="sup">[c]</char>, able to reign in
        his entire body<char style="sup">[B]</char> as well. <verse eid="JAS 3:2" />
      <verse number="3" style="v" sid="JAS 3:3" />Now we<char style="sup">[d]</char> stick bits in the mouths of horses in order to prevail upon them to
        do our bidding, and <char style="it">in doing so </char>we guide their entire bodies. <verse eid="JAS 3:3" />
      <verse number="4" style="v" sid="JAS 3:4" />Ships too, for example, are gigantic and are propelled by stiff breezes, guided by the smallest <char
        style="it">thing imaginable</char>—a rudder—in whatever heading the helmsman selects. <verse eid="JAS 3:4" />
      <verse number="5" style="v" sid="JAS 3:5" />Analogous to this, the tongue is a small part <char style="it">of a much larger unit</char> and makes
        outrageous remarks<char style="sup">[C]</char>.</para>
    <para style="p" vid="JAS 3:5">I’m telling you what, <char style="it">it’s like they say: </char>“Just a tiny flame can set even an
        enormous forest on fire<char style="sup">[e]</char>.” <verse eid="JAS 3:5"/>
      <verse number="6" style="v" sid="JAS 3:6" />And the tongue is a flame <char style="it">indeed</char>, an elaborate mechanism<char style="sup">[f]</char>
        of wrong-doing—the tongue occupies a position of preeminence<char style="sup">[g]</char> among our body
        parts—the defiler of the entire body and stoker of the Merry-go-round of Life<char style="sup">[D]</char>—and
        is itself stoked by hell.<verse eid="JAS 3:6" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="7" style="v" sid="JAS 3:7" />In fact, human beings by nature tame wild animals. All sorts—land, aquatic, reptilian—are <char style="it">in
        the process of</char> being tamed and have been tamed, <verse eid="JAS 3:7" />
      <verse number="8" style="v" sid="JAS 3:8" />but not a single person can tame the restless, unstable tongue, full of deadly poison. <verse eid="JAS 3:8" />
      <verse number="9" style="v" sid="JAS 3:9" />With it we thank the Father-God<char style="sup">[h]</char> and with it we swear at <char style="it">our
        fellow</char> man, those who have been created in the image of God. <verse eid="JAS 3:9" />
      <verse number="10" style="v" sid="JAS 3:10" />Out of the same mouth come thanksgiving and cussing. This is not the way it’s supposed to be, my comrades.<verse eid="JAS 3:10" />
      <verse number="11" style="v" sid="JAS 3:11" />Non-contaminated and contaminated <char style="it">water</char> doesn’t pour out of the same spring,
        now does it? <verse eid="JAS 3:11" />
      <verse number="12" style="v" sid="JAS 3:12" />It’s not possible, my comrades, for a fig tree to yield olives or a grape vine figs, or for <char style="it">a
        </char>water<char style="it"> source</char> to produce <char style="it">both </char>salt water <char
        style="it">and</char> fresh water, is it?<verse eid="JAS 3:12" />
    </para>
    <para style="p">
      <verse number="13" style="v" sid="JAS 3:13" />Who among you is wise and understanding? Let him display his deeds which come from the good conduct <char
        style="it">of one who follow’s God’s commandments </char>in wisdom’s gentleness. <verse eid="JAS 3:13" />
      <verse number="14" style="v" sid="JAS 3:14" />But if you have bitter jealousy and rivalry in your heart, don’t distort the truth by bragging and lying<char
        style="sup">[i]</char>. <verse eid="JAS 3:14" />
      <verse number="15" style="v" sid="JAS 3:15" />This is not the same wisdom which comes from the spiritual world where God lives<char style="sup">[j]</char>,
        but <char style="it">is the cunning-sort of wisdom which</char> is <char style="it">among other things
        </char>ruthlessly pragmatic, psychopathic, and diabolic<char style="sup">[E]</char>. <verse eid="JAS 3:15" />
      <verse number="16" style="v" sid="JAS 3:16" />The fact is, where jealousy and rivalry <char style="it">exist</char>, there is turmoil, and every bad
        thing imaginable is done<char style="sup">[k]</char>. <verse eid="JAS 3:16" />
      <verse number="17" style="v" sid="JAS 3:17" />But the wisdom from the spiritual world where God lives is pure and innocent, then <char style="it">on
        top of that is </char>peaceful, considerate, reasonable, full of mercy, and without pretense. <verse eid="JAS 3:17" />
      <verse number="18" style="v" sid="JAS 3:18" />The end-result where everything turns out right has its origins<char style="sup">[i]</char> in peace
        by those who put peace into practice.<verse eid="JAS 3:18" />
    </para>
